body:
I had code like this:

```rust
#![no_main]
#[no_mangle]
pub extern "C" fn main(_argc: isize, _arg: *const *const u8) -> isize {
    // ...
    loop {
        // ...
        if something.len() == 0 {
            break;
        }
        // ...
    }
}
```

which the compiler refused to compile, saying:
```
   |
32 |                 break;
   |                 ^^^^^ expected (), found isize
   |
   = note: expected type `()`
              found type `isize`

```

I'll pass on the fact that expected vs. found is often confusing, and that's one of those cases, but it's completely non-obvious what to make of this error, until you realize that the function itself never returns a value.

If the loop itself didn't have a value (with a semi-colon after its closing brace), the error makes more sense:
```
3  |   pub extern "C" fn main(_argc: isize, _arg: *const *const u8) -> isize {
   |  _______________________________________________________________________^
4  | |     loop {
5  | |     
6  | |     
...  |
40 | |     };
41 | | }
   | |_^ expected isize, found ()
   |
   = note: expected type `isize`
              found type `()`
```
